 <fr:p>The <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KI.xml"
addr="jms-00KI"
title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">identity function</fr:link> is clearly <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KI.xml"
addr="jms-00KI"
title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">injective</fr:link>, as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0=a_1]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0=a_1]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\rightarrowtail  B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  B\rightarrowtail  C]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00M0.xml"
addr="jms-00M0"
title="The axiom of infinity">injections</fr:link>. To show that the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KI.xml"
addr="jms-00KI"
title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">composite function</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\circ  f\colon  A\to  C]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injective</fr:link>, we fix <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0,a_1\in  A]]></fr:tex> to check that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g{\mathopen {}\left (f{\mathopen {}\left (a_0\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}} = g{\mathopen {}\left (f{\mathopen {}\left (a_1\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0=a_1]]></fr:tex>. Because <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injective</fr:link>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a_0\right )\mathclose {}}=f{\mathopen {}\left (a_1\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>; therefore, because <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injective</fr:link>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0=a_1]]></fr:tex> as desired.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:p>Now that we have enough definitions in hand to see it, the import of <fr:ref
addr="jms-00M7"
href="jms-00M7.xml"
taxon="Theorem" /> is then to state that a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KF.xml"
addr="jms-00KF"
title="Function">function</fr:link> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijective</fr:link> if and only if it is both <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injective</fr:link> and <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00M8.xml"
addr="jms-00M8"
title="Surjection">surjective</fr:link>.</fr:p><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2058</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00N4</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00N4.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Counting injections between finite sets">Counting <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injections</fr:link> between <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00LX.xml"
addr="jms-00LX"
title="Finite set">finite sets</fr:link></fr:title><fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00LX.xml"
addr="jms-00LX"
title="Finite set">finite sets</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we can describe number of <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injections</fr:link> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> as follows:</fr:p><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[  \mathord {\#}{\mathrm {Inj}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}} =  \begin {cases}   {\mathord {\#}{B}\choose \mathord {\#}{A}}\cdot  {\mathopen {}\left (\mathord {\#}{A}\right )\mathclose {}}! &\text {when } \mathord {\#}{A}\leq  \mathord {\#}{B}   \\   0 &\text {otherwise}  \end {cases} ]]></fr:tex>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2061</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#373</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-373.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We will argue from a combinatoric perspective.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>An <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injection</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> associates no more than one <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> to the same <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  B]]></fr:tex>. Thus if we consider the subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U\subseteq  B]]></fr:tex> spanned by elements of the form <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, we should then get a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>as each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  U]]></fr:tex> comes from a <fr:em>unique</fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Therefore, choosing an <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injection</fr:link> amounts to making <fr:em>two</fr:em> independent choices: first we choose a subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> that is in <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and then we choose a <fr:em>specific</fr:em> <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to that subset. The number of such subsets is precisely <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{B}\choose  \mathord {\#}{A}]]></fr:tex>, and we have already seen in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00KT"
href="jms-00KT.xml"
taxon="Proposition" /> that the number of such bijections is the factorial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\mathord {\#}{A}!\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Of course, if there is no subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> equinumerous with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then there can be no <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injection</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
